# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 0\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  PURPOSE OF THIS FAMILY\
\
This family addresses:\
\
Fear-based threat prediction loops:\
\
* Social anxiety\
* Performance anxiety\
* Financial anxiety\
* Fear of flying\
* Health anxiety\
* Relationship anxiety\
* Fear of failure\
* Fear of rejection\
\
All subtypes must map to the same core mechanism:\
\
> Threat Detection 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  Future Prediction 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  Nervous System Arousal 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  Avoidance 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  Reinforcement\
\
If a topic does not map cleanly to this mechanism, it does not belong in this family.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 1\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  AUTHOR VOICE MODEL (Non-Negotiable)\
\
## Identity\
\
The author is:\
\
* A pattern-noticer\
* A reflective observer\
* Not a therapist\
* Not a guru\
* Not the hero of the story\
\
The author:\
\
* Tells stories of others (90%)\
* Interprets patterns\
* Shares findings\
* Speaks with grounded authority\
\
---\
\
## Voice Rules\
\
Allowed tone:\
\
* \'93I started noticing\'85\'94\
* \'93This pattern shows up a lot.\'94\
* \'93What\'92s interesting is\'85\'94\
* \'93Here\'92s what I\'92ve seen.\'94\
\
Forbidden:\
\
* \'93You must.\'94\
* \'93You should.\'94\
* Clinical lecturing.\
* Outcome promises.\
* Fixing language.\
\
No preaching.\
No savior tone.\
No superiority.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 2\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  BOOK-LEVEL ARC (12 CHAPTERS)\
\
The book follows a 4-phase emotional journey.\
\
---\
\
## PHASE I \'97 HARDSHIP (Recognition)\
\
**Goal:** Normalize activation.\
\
Ch 1 \'97 Anxiety Is an Alarm\
Power Point: This is a nervous system response, not a flaw.\
\
Ch 2 \'97 The Body Reacts First\
Power Point: The body fires before thinking catches up.\
\
Ch 3 \'97 The Cost of Constant Prediction\
Power Point: Living in imagined futures reinforces fear.\
\
---\
\
## PHASE II \'97 UNDERSTANDING (Mechanism Clarity)\
\
**Goal:** Reveal loop mechanics.\
\
Ch 4 \'97 The Pattern Repeats\
Power Point: Same trigger 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  same reaction 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  same avoidance.\
\
Ch 5 \'97 The Brain Is Overprotective\
Power Point: The mind exaggerates danger and underestimates recovery.\
\
Ch 6 \'97 Activation Is Not Danger\
Power Point: High arousal does not equal high threat.\
\
---\
\
## PHASE III \'97 EXPERIMENTATION (Behavior Shift)\
\
**Goal:** Introduce regulated exposure.\
\
Ch 7 \'97 Staying Instead of Escaping\
Power Point: Avoidance teaches the alarm to stay loud.\
\
Ch 8 \'97 Testing Predictions\
Power Point: Most predictions collapse under real experience.\
\
Ch 9 \'97 Acting Before Feeling Ready\
Power Point: Action reshapes fear more than reassurance.\
\
---\
\
## PHASE IV \'97 EXPANSION (Identity Growth)\
\
**Goal:** Expand life beyond vigilance.\
\
Ch 10 \'97 Capacity Expands\
Power Point: The nervous system recalibrates through repetition.\
\
Ch 11 \'97 Recovery Builds Trust\
Power Point: The body knows how to return to baseline.\
\
Ch 12 \'97 Building a Life Larger Than Fear\
Power Point: Fear can exist without controlling behavior.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 3\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  CHAPTER STRUCTURE (Locked Format)\
\
Every chapter contains 10 sections.\
\
1. HOOK (Thesis framed in lived observation)\
2. SCENE (Open-loop trigger moment)\
3. REFLECTION (Pattern recognition)\
4. EXERCISE (Grounding or regulation)\
5. STORY (Closed-loop arc)\
6. INSIGHT (Mechanism clarified)\
7. SCENE (Pattern repetition)\
8. EXERCISE (Behavioral or exposure experiment)\
9. STORY (Shift demonstration)\
10. INTEGRATION (Expansion statement)\
\
Structure cannot change.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 4\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  SCENE RULES (Open Loop Units)\
\
Scenes:\
\
* Are short\
* Are sensory\
* Contain a concrete trigger\
* Include at least one physiological marker\
* Do NOT interpret\
* Do NOT resolve\
\
Example components:\
\
* Environmental detail\
* Physical sensation\
* Micro-behavior\
* Silent tension\
\
Scenes exist to create identification.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 5\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  STORY RULES (Closed Loop Units)\
\
Stories must:\
\
* Contain a beginning trigger\
* Show internal reaction\
* Demonstrate avoidance or pattern\
* Show a shift (small or large)\
* End with a resolved outcome\
\
Stories prove the thesis.\
\
Stories cannot end abstractly.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 6\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  EXERCISE INSERTION RULES\
\
Exercises are selected by functional type, not theme.\
\
Each chapter must contain:\
\
* One grounding exercise\
* One behavior-based experiment or prediction audit\
\
Exercises must:\
\
* Follow 4-part structure (intro 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  guided 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  aha 
\f6 \cf2 \cb5 \uc0\u8594 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  integration)\
* Use second person\
* Avoid outcome promises\
* Avoid \'93fixing\'94 language\
\
Exercise type must match chapter thesis.\
\
Example:\
\
If thesis = \'93Prediction exaggerates danger\'94\
Use:\
\
* Breath regulation\
* Prediction testing\
* Exposure micro-step\
\
Not unrelated grounding content.\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 7\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  OVERLAY DESIGN (Subtype Compatibility)\
\
Subtypes only change:\
\
1. Threat object\
2. Core prediction statement\
3. Avoidance behavior\
4. Body signature\
\
Everything else remains structurally identical.\
\
Example:\
\
Social anxiety:\
Threat: rejection\
Prediction: \'93They\'92ll judge me.\'94\
Avoidance: silence\
Body: throat tight\
\
Financial anxiety:\
Threat: loss\
Prediction: \'93I\'92ll lose everything.\'94\
Avoidance: not checking accounts\
Body: chest pressure\
\
---\
\
# 
\f2 \cf2 \cb5 8\uc0\u65039 \u8419 
\f0 \cf2 \cb5  ARC OVERLAY COMPATIBILITY\
